abstract.p:
Magneto-hydrodynamic double-diffusive natural convection in a cavity is numerically investigated in the present work. Al2O3, Cu, and Ag based nanofluids in a square cavity with a thermal and solute source in the center, and uniform magnetic field are considered. The Patel model is employed to estimate the thermal conductivity of applied nanofluids, and the numerical calculation is based on the implementation of the lattice Boltzmann method and utilizing the standard D2Q9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_{2} Q_{9}$$\end{document} model to study the heat transfer, and also species concentration. A parametric study is carried out to observe the influence of the type, the volume fraction of nanoparticle (ϕ=0-5%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi = 0 - 5\%$$\end{document}), Rayleigh (Ra=104-105-106)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Ra = 10^{4} - 10^{5} - 10^{6} )$$\end{document}, Lewis 0.1-2-10\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( {0.1 - 2 - 10} \right)$$\end{document}, and Hartmann number 10-20-100\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( {10 - 20 - 100} \right)$$\end{document} on average Nusselt and Sherwood numbers, flow fields, temperature, and concentration distribution. The results show that an augment in nanoparticle volume fraction and Rayleigh number increased the average Nusselt and Sherwood numbers. Lewis number showed a significant impact on mass transfer rate. However, it did not affect the heat transfer rate remarkably. Applying a magnetic field caused a reduction in flow circulation which resulted in a decline in heat and mass transfer. A comparison of the simulation outcome with the available data shows that the generated code perfectly captures the fluid flow behavior and heat transfer process as a function of the affecting parameters.

sec.p:
The selection of an optimized nanoparticle in the based fluid has a key role in heat and mass transfer efficiencies. The affecting parameters include allowable concentration and size, shape, aspect ratio, temperature, base fluid, pH, stability, etc. The present research tries to address and investigate the heat and mass transfer of Al2O3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Al_{2} O_{3}$$\end{document}, Cu, and Ag water-based nanofluid from the thermos-physical perspective. Accordingly, the rightful based fluid for Ag nanoparticles is toluene and water, for Cu nanoparticles are water, oil, ethylene glycol, acetone, and for Al2O3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Al_{2} O_{3}$$\end{document} is water, ethylene glycol, pump oil, water + glycerine [29]. Some of the important features of nanofluid industrialization including stability are missing, and are currently under research. There are not solid available data on the number of industrial-scale successful adaptation of nanofluids.

The main goal of the present work is to numerically investigate the double-diffusive natural heat and mass transfer in an enclosure with an internally located heat and solute source filled with nanofluid in the presence of an imposed horizontal magnetic field. This study investigates the combined effect of temperature and solute gradient in the presence of magnetic field in the particular geometry and the relevant fluid flow pattern due to the temperature and solute concentration gradients. The adopted geometry is a simple applicable geometry in many industrial uses. The lattice Boltzmann method for numerical calculation and standard D2Q9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_{2} Q_{9}$$\end{document} model are utilized to model the heat transfer, fluid flow, and species concentration as a more novel method than the conventional method. The flow is considered as steady-state and laminar, and the Patel model is used to predict the thermal conductivity of nanofluid, restricted to spherical nanoparticles.

The two-dimensional square cavity is considered and is presented schematically in Fig. 1. Both the inner and the outer walls of the enclosure are uniformly permeable enough to maintain solute absorption from the inner contaminated secondary fluid and adsorption of the outer clean secondary fluid. It is also assumed that the secondary fluid is bulky enough to maintain constant temperature and concentration on internal and external enclosure walls. This condition is achievable by a steady axial flow of the secondary fluid. Under the preceding circumstances, enclosure’s external walls are exposed to a constant temperature and concentration of magnitudes Tc,Cc,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Tc, Cc,$$\end{document} and the enclosure’s internal walls are kept at constant temperature and concentration of magnitudes Th,Ch\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$T_{h} , C_{h}$$\end{document}. It is worth mentioning that in the present research the radiation heat transfer from walls to nanofluid did not consider and the nanofluids treated as a single phase liquid.Fig. 1
Schematic of the problem geometry

The nanoparticles volume fraction is assumed uniform in the convective flow domain in the cavity. Although nanoparticles distribution can be affected by electromagnetic forces as the fluid is being circulated continuously due to temperature and solute concentration gradients, the nanoparticles are redistributed repeatedly and therefore uniformity in the nanoparticles volume fraction is a realistic assumption in this problem. Additionally, the base fluid and the nanoparticles are assumed to be at thermal equilibrium. The properties of adopted nanoparticles and the pure fluid are presented in Table 1 and are considered to be constant. The density in the buoyancy force term is calculated by the Boussinesq’s approximation. Besides, a magnetic field operates in the horizontal direction at all points of the flow field. According to Ohm’s law, law of conservation of charge and Lorentz force law, the electric current density J\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
