In Figs. 8 and 9, the Rayleigh number is kept constant at Ra=106\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Ra = 10^{6}$$\end{document}, to investigate the effect of variation in Lewis number. These figures represent that Lewis number has a considerable influence on the mass transfer rate in terms of Sherwood number but has less effect on the heat transfer rate in terms of Nusselt number. This can be explained by the fact that the mass diffusivity coefficient and as a result of Lewis number only appears in the diffusion term of concentration equation and will not perturb other equations significantly. For the same reason, as shown in Fig. 10, the Lewis number has not a significant effect on the streamlines and isotherms. Therefore, the average Nusselt number is almost independent of the Lewis number. This is the result of negligible changes in thermal contours concerning Lewis number for the preceding reasons. The results illustrate significant variations in the concentration contours due to the increment in the mass diffusivity value of the solute species through nanofluid as the Lewis number increases.Fig. 8
