In Figs. 11 and 12, the effect of Hartmann number on the average Nusselt and Sherwood number for a particular case (Ra=106,Le=2,Ha=0-20-100\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Ra = 10^{6} , Le = 2, Ha = 0 - 20 - 100$$\end{document}) is shown for different nanoparticles volume fraction. For a specific value of nanoparticle volume fraction, the Hartmann number represents the intensity of the imposed magnetic field to the fluid flow. Results demonstrate that at constant nanoparticle volume fraction effect of an increase in the intensity of the magnetic field in terms of Hartmann number is to decrease heat and mass transfer rate in the cavity which represented in terms of reduction in Nusselt and Sherwood numbers. This reduction is more observable in nanofluids with higher values of nanoparticle volume fraction. The effect can be explained in Fig. 13 for both cases of pure fluid and nanofluid convection in the cavity. As can be seen from Fig. 13 for both values of ϕ=0.0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi = 0.0$$\end{document} and ϕ=0.05\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi = 0.05$$\end{document}, the external horizontal magnetic field dampens flow circulation in the cavity due to induced bulk forces exerted in the opposite direction of fluid flow which prevents the flow to circulate in the cavity and consequently reduces heat and mass transfer in terms of Nusselt and Sherwood number respectively. In other words, bulk Lorentz forces attributed to the magnetic field oppose bulk gravitational forces in the flow domain.Fig. 11
